%md
## Import, Clean and Save Dataset
This notebook uses the Netflix Movies and Shows dataset to show the following processes.
1. Importing csv data
2. Looking at the inferred schema - eg. what does Spark believe the value type of each column represents
3. Creating temporary views (eg. `CREATE view netflix_raw`)
4. Using Spark SQL interpreter to view the loaded table

Import, Clean and Save Dataset

This notebook uses the Netflix Movies and Shows dataset to show the following processes.
1. Importing csv data
2. Looking at the inferred schema - eg. what does Spark believe the value type of each column represents
3. Creating temporary views (eg. CREATE view netflix_raw)
4. Using Spark SQL interpreter to view the loaded table

paragraphs.text:
%spark

import spark.implicits._
import org.apache.spark.sql._
import org.apache.spark.sql.functions._
import org.apache.spark.sql.types._

val BaseFilePath = "file:///learn"
val NetflixTitlesRaw = "/netflix/netflix_titles_raw.csv"
val NetflixTitlesFormatted = "/netflix/netflix_titles.csv"

val netflixData = spark.read
  //.option("mode", "FAILFAST | DROPMALFORMED")
  .option("header", "true")
  .option("inferSchema", "true")
  .option("encoding", "UTF-8")
  .csv(s"$BaseFilePath/$NetflixTitlesFormatted")

// see the underlying inferredSchema
netflixData.printSchema
val inferredSchema = netflixData.schema
netflixData.createOrReplaceTempView("netflix_raw")
spark.sql("show tables").show

%md
## Reimport the Netflix Movie Data using our StructType
Q. Why would you use a Strict Schema vs Schema Inference?

In the next paragraph we do the following.
1. Opt-out of schema inference
2. Directly apply our `strictSchema` when parsing our CSV
3. Lastly we create a new table called `netflix` which is backed by our `netflixDataStrict` DataFrame

msg.data:
Reimport the Netflix Movie Data using our StructType

Q. Why would you use a Strict Schema vs Schema Inference?

In the next paragraph we do the following.
1. Opt-out of schema inference
2. Directly apply our strictSchema when parsing our CSV
3. Lastly we create a new table called netflix which is backed by our netflixDataStrict DataFrame

paragraphs.text:
%spark
//https://docs.databricks.com/data/data-sources/read-csv.html
val netflixDataStrict = spark.read
  .option("header", "true")
  .option("sep", ",")
  .option("quote", "\"")
  .option("inferSchema", "false")
  .schema(strictSchema)
  .option("encoding", "UTF-8")
  .csv(s"$BaseFilePath/$NetflixTitlesFormatted")

netflixDataStrict.createOrReplaceTempView("netflix")

netflixDataStrict.printSchema

spark.sql("desc netflix").show()

%md
## Using Intersect and Except on Two DataFrames
Gain more control over conditional where clauses
1. Sometimes reducing one DataFrame by another is easier than a complex query

msg.data:
Using Intersect and Except on Two DataFrames

Gain more control over conditional where clauses
1. Sometimes reducing one DataFrame by another is easier than a complex query

paragraphs.text:
%spark
val cleanTypes = netflixData.select("*").where(col("type").isInCollection(Seq("Movie", "TV Show")))

val cleaned = cleanTypes.count
val all = netflixDataStrict.count

// this can be more complex logic - for simplicity this is basically a `select * from netflix where id NOT IN (select show_id from netflix where type = 'Movie')`
val intersection = netflixDataStrict.intersect(cleanTypes.where(col("type").equalTo("Movie")))
val tvShows = netflixDataStrict.except(intersection)
tvShows.sort(asc("show_id")).show()

%md
### Using a Subquery to reduce your Data (The SQL Way)
The following is an example of using subqueries in Spark. This subquery return one or more records of a single type.

Q. What is the difference between a SubQuery and a Scalar SubQuery?

In the example below, we use the inner SQL query `select show_id from netflix where type = 'MOVIE'` to return a SET of ids as input to our `IN` clause. The outer query is then dependent on the result of the inner query to filter the Universal Set of Netflix content. Yielding the set of Shows instead of movies.

%spark

val netflixWithTimeDimension = netflixDataStrict
  .withColumn("datetime", functions.to_timestamp(col("date_added"), "MMMMM dd, yyyy"))
  .withColumn("release_month", functions.date_format(col("datetime"), "M"))
  .withColumn("release_day", functions.date_format(col("datetime"), "d"))

val newTableDDL = netflixWithTimeDimension.schema.toDDL

## Exercise: Investigate the Netflix Data
1. Try seeing if the patterns of release changes for TV Shows or Movies
2. What seems to be the best time of year to release a new Show?
3. Is there anything interesting you can find?

## Saving your hardwork into Redis
1. Saving the Data as Binary (Serialized) or not Serialized
2. Look at the underlying Redis Data (keys *)
3. Debug the Object size

msg.data:
Saving your hardwork into Redis

  1. Saving the Data as Binary (Serialized) or not Serialized
  2. Look at the underlying Redis Data (keys *)
  3. Debug the Object size

paragraphs.text:
%spark
// write the updated data to redis
// use binary serialization to reduce the cost of storing this data in redis
netflixWithTimeDimension
  .write
  .format("org.apache.spark.sql.redis")
  .mode("overwrite")      
  .option("table", "netflix")
  .option("model", "binary")
  .option("key.column", "show_id")
  .save()

%md
## Let us inspect the data using Redis CLI
1. Open up a new terminal window. `docker exec -it redis5 redis-cli`
2. View all of the Keys. `keys *`
3. Take a look at the Serialized Size of the Data. `debug object netflix_norm:80123742` and `debug object netflix:80123742`
4. If you want to remove all keys `flushall`. Note: Flushall will delete everything and let you start over

msg.data:
Let us inspect the data using Redis CLI

  1. Open up a new terminal window. docker exec -it redis5 redis-cli
  2. View all of the Keys. keys *
  3. Take a look at the Serialized Size of the Data. debug object netflix_norm:80123742 and debug object netflix:80123742
  4. If you want to remove all keys flushall. Note: Flushall will delete everything and let you start over
